commit.message:
Fix gpg>=1.4.18 bug where --edit-key continually asks for a passphrase.

This is a really gross hack.

The problem is that, with gpg>=1.4.18, there appears to be absolutely no way
to tell it to not ask for a passphrase on stdin if the first passphrase
given to it was wrong.  None of the options that are supposed to stop it
from doing this actually work: not `--no-tty`, not `--batch`, not
`--passphrase-fd 0`, nothing.  It'll just hang there forever like a drooling
idiot.  (Thanks, howler monkeys.)

So!  This gross hack will feed it the expiration timestamp as a second wrong
passphrase to get it to finally give the fuck up.  (I seriously hope that no
uses their key expiration as actual key passphrase, but even if so, this
will also fix the bug.)
